  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: Because of his influence, Rizal was considered a threat by the Spanish
    government. He was arrested and exiled to Dapitan, where he continued to serve
    the community by teaching, practicing medicine, and helping improve local life.
    In 1896, he was accused of involvement in the Philippine Revolution, arrested,
    and brought back to Manila. He was sentenced to death and executed on December
    30, 1896, at Bagumbayan (now Luneta Park). His death inspired Filipinos to continue
    the fight for freedom, and he is now remembered as the national hero of the Philippines,
    symbolizing intelligence, courage, and peaceful resistance.
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 8a89fa14b10d46a99122fd4f73fca9a2, type: 2}
